Can Money and Population Size Buy Happiness?

1. Introduction

Happiness is an important factor in so many facets of our lives and is influenced by so many different factors that it is hard to fully grasp. However, the Happiness Report has taken on this task and created a happiness score for most countries based on a variety of factors such as freedom to make life choices, social support and many more. We wanted to look and see if the scores given by this organization had any correlation to other factors that may not have been considered within the original report.

a. Set up

First load the packages used throughout the document.

b. Quick description of the datasets

Since the report uses data from 2019-2021, we chose to look at the change in total population and GDP between 2019-2021. To do this we looked at total population and GDP per country at both 2019 and 2021 and will find the difference between the two values to then compare to the happiness score of their respective country.

Each unique row in the datasets represent a specific country and every variable apart from the countries are numerical while the countries are categorical. Finally, we expect to join our 3 datasets together through the key ‘Country’.

# Upload data sets from folder
happiness <- read_csv("Country Happiness Data.csv")
gdp <- read_csv("GDP.csv")
population <- read_csv("Population.csv")

c. Define a research question

We wanted to look and see if the scores given by this organization had any correlation to other factors that may not have been considered within the original report. Our research questions are:

  1. Does the GDP between 2021 and 2019 have a relationship with a country’s happiness score?
  2. Does a country’s total population change between 2021 and 2019 have an effect on their happiness score?

We expect to see a positive linear relationship between GDP and happiness score while we expect to see a normal distribution when it comes to total population and happiness score.

2. Tidying Part 1

In order to join together the 3 datasets we first had to create new columns for our ‘gdpdiff’ and ‘popdiff’ as well as rename a few columns to make them more accurate and easily called.

# creating a new column and tidying population data into a new dataset
pop1 <- population %>%
  rename(pop.2019 = `2019`,
         pop.2021 = `2021`) %>%
  mutate(popdiff = pop.2021 - pop.2019)

# renaming variable names and calculating gdp difference 
gdp1 <- gdp %>%
  rename(gdp.2019 = `2019 [YR2019]`,
         gdp.2021 = `2021 [YR2021]`) %>%
  mutate(gdpdiff = gdp.2021 - gdp.2019)

3. Joining/Merging

We used ‘anti_join’ to look at what countries did not match in order to figure out what countries had different names between the datasets. We renamed a few countries because the names for each specific country were not the same and in order for the ‘left_join’ to work the names needed to be the same.

# checking if there are matches for all countries between happiness and 'gdp1'
anti_join(happiness, gdp1, by = c("Country" = "Country Name"))

# joining 'gdp2' into 'happiness' and putting it into 'happiness1'
happiness1 <- left_join(happiness, gdp2, by = c("Country" = "Country Name"))

# joining ‘pop2’ into ‘happiness1’ and replace new data set into ‘happiness1’
happiness1 <- left_join(happiness1, pop2, by = "Country")

The only ID variables that were the same between the 3 datasets was “Country” while every other one was unique to that specific dataset. Then ‘inner_join’ was used using the variable ‘Country’ to combine ‘gdp2’ and ‘pop2’ into the new combined dataset ‘happiness1’. No ID variables were left out of the new ‘happiness 1’ dataset. 54 observations were dropped when ‘pop2’ joined into ‘happiness1’, 72 observations were dropped when ‘gdp2’ joined into ‘happiness1’, but ‘happiness1’ remained at 147 observations when these two datasets joined it. Some potential issues include NA values that may exist due to certain countries existing in one data set but not another as well as too many unnecessary variables in our new combined dataset.

4. Tidying Part 2

After joining all the datasets, we needed to tidy some more!

# tidying joined data into new dataset
happiness2 <- happiness1 %>%
  select(-c(Rank, `Series Name`, `Series Code`)) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c('gdp.2019', 'gdp.2021', 'pop.2019', 'pop.2021')) %>%
  separate(name, into = c("type", "year")) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = type,
              values_from = value) %>%
  na.omit()

In order to tidy our data set we split the columns ‘gdp.2019’, ‘gdp.2021’, ‘pop.2019’, and ‘pop.2021’ into new columns based using ‘pivot_longer’ and ‘pivot_wider’. First these original columns were split apart based on year and value and then renamed into type and year using ‘pivot_longer’ and then the ‘type’ columns were split into ‘gdp’ and ‘pop’ using ‘pivot_wider’. NA values were then removed from the new tidied ‘happiness 2’ dataset.

This shows us that over time the median GDP and population goes up over time along with the number of low scores. This signifies that there may be an inverse relationship between population/GDP and happiness scores.

6. Visualizations

a. Graph 1: Happiness Frequency Plot

# create frequency plot for happiness score
happiness3 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Happiness score`)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "darkolivegreen4", binwidth = 1) +
  labs(x = "Happiness Score", 
       y = "Frequency", 
       title = "Frequency Distribution of Happiness Scores") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,9,1))

The graph above shows a distribution of the frequency of happiness scores of all the countries in our dataset. It shows a relatively normal distribution that is skewed to the left with the greatest frequency of happiness scores in the 6 range. This shows us that most countries have above average happiness, but on the far ends of the graph more countries have really low happiness scores than really high happiness scores. Therefore, it seems that a country is more likely to be slightly above average or below average in happiness than to be highly above average in happiness.

b. Graph 2: Population Difference Frequency Plot

# create frequency plot for population difference
happiness3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = popdiff)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "mediumpurple1", bins = 30) +
  labs(x = "Population Difference", 
       y = "Frequency", 
       title = "Frequency of Population Difference Between 2019-2021") +
  ylim(0,35)

The graph shows a frequency distribution for population change between 2019-21. It shows that most countries either experienced no population change or a negligible amount. However, more countries gained population than lost population as there are relatively more countries with population gains than losses and therefore shows a relatively right skewed plot.

c. Graph 3: Happiness based on GDP per capita vs. GDP Difference

# create plot for happiness score explained by gdp per capita vs GDP difference
happiness3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `Explained by: GDP per capita`, y = gdpdiff)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(x = "Happiness explained by GDP per capita", 
       y = "GDP Difference (Current LCU)", 
       title = "Happiness explained by GDP per capita vs GDP difference") +
  xlim(0.5, 2.15)

The scatterplot above illustrates the relationship between GDP difference between 2019-21 and the portion of the happiness score explained by GDP per capita within this same time period. Surprisingly there seems to be no correlation between the two. Even as more of the happiness score is explained by GDP, indicating that more of the score was impacted by the country’s GDP, the GDP difference over the designated time period stayed mostly the same at 0. There do appear to be some outliers as more of the score is determined by GDP with a handful of countries showing a large growth in GDP, however there were not enough for it to be considered a proper relationship

Surprisingly there seems to be no correlation between the two. Even as more of the happiness score is explained by GDP, indicating that more of the score was impacted by the country’s GDP, the GDP difference over the designated time period stayed mostly the same at 0. There do appear to be some outliers as more of the score is determined by GDP with a handful of countries showing a large growth in GDP, however there were not enough for it to be considered a proper relationship.

e. Graph 5: Country, Happiness, and Population Changes

# create plot for country, happiness score, and population difference 
happiness3 %>%

The histogram above shows each countries happiness score by the length of the countries respective bar length while showing the magnitude of the population difference between 2019-21. A larger happiness score represents a happier country while a lower score represents a less happy country. A lighter bar color corresponds to a greater population change while a darker bar color corresponds to a smaller population change. There does not appear to be any relationship between happiness score and population change per country. Countries with low population change appear both as countries with low and high happiness scores and the same can be said by countries with high happiness scores.

f. Graph 6: Country, Happiness, and GDP Changes

# create plot for country, happiness score, and gdp difference
happiness3 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = `Happiness score`, y = `Country Code`, fill = gdpdiff)) +

The histogram above shows each country’s happiness score by the length of the bar while the color represents the difference in GDP of that respective country between 2019-21. The darker the color of the bar represents a smaller or a loss in GDP while a lighter color represents a growth in GDP. Despite the varying happiness scores across countries there does not appear to be a relationship between GDP and happiness score. Most countries fall within a certain color range for GDP and the few outliers in color aren’t necessarily high or low in happiness score. Therefore based on this graph no relationship can be seen.

7. Discussion

Based on all of our graphs and summaries we can conclude that there is no relationship between happiness score and both GDP difference and population difference between 2019 and 2021. Initially, based on our summary table we thought that there was an inverse relationship between population/GDP growth and happiness scores because the number of low happiness scores increased as the population and GDP growed. The first clue that this was not the case was the frequency graphs of both the population difference and happiness score because graph 2 showed little diversity with the vast majority of countries exhibiting no population growth while graph 1 showed a lot more diversity in the amount of each score. This signaled to us that there may be a disconnect between the two variables. The next clue was graph 4 showing the relationships between GDP and population difference. This too was interesting because both variables seemed to suggest that there was little population change or GDP change within the time period with a few exceptions but nothing concrete enough to show one was influencing the other. Finally, graphs 5 and 6 showed the relationship between happiness score, GDP difference and population difference respectively. These graphs confirmed what was hinted at in the previous graphs as there was no apparent pattern or relationship between either happiness score and GDP difference or happiness score and population difference.

This project overall was challenging especially in figuring out how to merge and tidy our datasets and even further challenging how to visualize our dataset in a constructive way. Experimenting with different visualizations was time consuming and required a lot of trial and error. From this process we learned the importance of tidying and how surprisingly hard it is to get graphs that look legible.
